### Description

By default the order of css imports are defined by the order of the import statements (see issue #5312).

However, if the import statement contains a layer specification (like `@import 'somefile' layer(somlayer);`) it is treated as a css import and is moved to the top of the generated css file.

**Why is this a problem?**

The order of css layers can be pre-defined by declaring them without any styles: `@layer lay1, lay2, lay3;`
However, if a css import is moved to the top of the generated css file, the layer order will be somewhat ignored, see repro.

**Why not just change the import orders?**

We have a situation where one lib's stylesheet is already put in a layer, while another is not, and we want to put it in a layer as well. However, the order of these layers are important, so we must specify it beforehand which is not possible due to the current behaviour.

### Minimal Reproduction

Original styles.scss
```
// this defines the order of layers
@layer lib1, lib2;

// this imports the actual files into a given layer
// note the order of imports: lib2 first, lib1 second
@import 'lib2' layer(lib2);
@import 'lib1' layer(lib1);
```

The expected behaviour:
```
@layer lib1, lib2;
@layer lib2{
  // ... lib2 content
}
@layer lib1{
  // ... lib1 content
}
```

The actual behaviour:
```
@layer lib2{
  // ... lib2 content
}
@layer lib1{
  // ... lib1 content
}
@layer lib1, lib2;
```

Also see repo for complete repro: https://github.com/csisy-btw/css-layer-import-repro

